## Phase 1 — Project scaffold

```
Set up a new Python research project called `amc-tasksim` for simulating Adaptive
Mixed-Criticality (AMC) fixed-priority scheduling.

- Python 3.11+, dependency management via pyproject.toml (uv or plain pip, your choice).
- Core dependencies: numpy, pandas, matplotlib, pytest, tqdm, and joblib (or stdlib
  multiprocessing) for parallel experiment execution.
- Directory layout:
    amc_tasksim/generation/    # DRS algorithm + task-set generator
    amc_tasksim/scheduling/    # priority assignment + analytic schedulability tests
    amc_tasksim/simulation/    # event-driven simulator core
    amc_tasksim/experiments/   # sweep orchestration + result storage
    amc_tasksim/analysis/      # plotting/summary statistics
    tests/                     # pytest suite mirroring the package structure
    docs/                      # I will place three reference PDFs here
    results/                   # gitignored experiment output
- README.md summarising the project goal: generate large-scale synthetic AMC task sets across
  a utilisation sweep and a HI-criticality failure-probability sweep (FP = 1/N, N ranging over
  several orders of magnitude), then simulate each for a fixed duration to empirically measure
  degraded-mode behaviour (NiD, TiD, JNE, LDM, HDM).
- Initialise git, commit this scaffold.

Do not implement any algorithm logic yet — this is project setup only. When done, show me the
directory tree and confirm `pytest` runs cleanly (even with zero tests collected).
```

**Definition of done:** repo exists, `pytest` runs, tree matches the layout above.

