## Phase 4 — Priority assignment & analytic schedulability filter

```
Implement amc_tasksim/scheduling/priority.py and amc_tasksim/scheduling/amc_rtb.py.

priority.py: assign_deadline_monotonic(taskset) -> sets taskset.priority (lower Di = higher
priority; ties broken by task index). This is the default.

amc_rtb.py: implement the AMC-rtb schedulability test from docs/AMCRRTAS2022.pdf Section IV-A
(equations 1–2), or equivalently docs/CAMCRTNS2022.pdf Section 4.1 for the general form:
- Ri(LO) via standard fixed-priority response-time analysis (fixed-point iteration on eq. 1).
- Ri(HI) via eq. 2, accounting for HI-criticality interference at Cj(HI) and LO-criticality
  interference capped at Ri(LO).
Return per-task response times and an overall schedulable: bool.

Add a filter used by the generator (optional, applied in the experiment orchestration phase,
not baked into generate_taskset itself): keep only task sets that are (a) schedulable under
AMC-rtb, and (b) NOT schedulable under plain fixed-priority analysis assuming every task
executes at max(Ci(LO), Ci(HI)) — i.e. the task set genuinely needs the mixed-criticality
scheme to be viable, following the methodology in docs/AMCRRTAS2022.pdf Section V-C. Implement
this as amc_tasksim/scheduling/filters.py: is_nontrivial_amc_taskset(taskset) -> bool.

Tests: reproduce the worked 3-task example from docs/AMCRRTAS2022.pdf Appendix A by hand
(tau1: Clo=1,T=2; tau2: Clo=1,Chi=5,T=10; tau3: Clo=Chi=4,T=100,D=18) and confirm your AMC-rtb
implementation gives R3(LO)=10 and R3(HI)=19 (i.e. correctly reports tau3 as unschedulable under
AMC-rtb) — this is a known result from the paper and a strong regression check.
```

**Definition of done:** the Appendix-A worked example reproduces R3(LO)=10, R3(HI)=19 exactly.

