## Phase 5 — Event-driven simulator core

```
Implement amc_tasksim/simulation/engine.py: a discrete-event (not tick-by-tick) simulator for
fixed-priority preemptive scheduling of a single TaskSet on one core, running for a specified
duration in integer ticks (default 10**6).

Per-job execution time model (this is the stochastic core, distinct from the paper's fixed
default — here FP = 1/N is swept):
- LO-criticality task job: execution time ~ uniform(BCET_i, Ci(LO)), always completes within
  Ci(LO) by construction.
- HI-criticality task job: with probability FP = 1/N, exhibits HI-criticality behaviour
  (execution time ~ uniform(Ci(LO), Ci(HI))); otherwise behaves like a LO job
  (execution time ~ uniform(BCET_i, Ci(LO))).

Mode-change protocol (baseline = original AMC, from docs/AMCRRTAS2022.pdf Section III):
- Normal mode: all tasks release jobs.
- Enter degraded mode: the instant any active HI-criticality job has executed for Ci(LO)
  without completing.
- Degraded mode: new releases of LO-criticality tasks are dropped (not queued, not executed) —
  count each as a JNE event. HI-criticality jobs continue normally.
- Exit degraded mode: on the next idle instant (no active jobs of any task).

Implement the mode-change trigger as a small strategy interface (e.g. a ModeChangeProtocol
abstract base class with on_job_progress/on_completion/on_idle hooks) even though only the
original-AMC variant is implemented now — this is so Phase 9 can add AMC-RH/AMC-RA later
without touching the core engine.

As a defensive check (not expected to trigger given the execution-time model above, but a good
guard against generation bugs): if any job's realised execution time exceeds its enforced budget
(Ci(HI) for HI-criticality tasks, Ci(LO) for LO-criticality tasks in normal mode), abort the job
and log a warning rather than silently continuing.

Metrics collected per run, matching docs/AMCRRTAS2022.pdf Section V-A:
- HDM: count of HI-criticality deadline misses (should always be 0 for a schedulable task set —
  treat any non-zero HDM as a flagged anomaly in the output, not just a number).
- JNE: count of LO-criticality jobs dropped in degraded mode.
- LDM: count of LO-criticality jobs that executed but missed their deadline.
- TiD: total time spent in degraded mode, as a fraction of simulation duration.
- NiD: number of times degraded mode was entered.
- Additionally: total HI-criticality job releases per task and total HI-behaviour "trigger"
  events observed (jobs that actually exceeded Ci(LO)) — needed later to check whether a given
  (U, N) combination produced enough rare events to be statistically meaningful.

For testing/validation purposes, support an optional deterministic override where job release
times are supplied explicitly rather than generated from periods/randomness (needed for Phase 6).

Function signature: simulate(taskset, duration=10**6, seed=..., mode_protocol=OriginalAMC()) -> SimulationResult (a dataclass with the metrics above).
```

**Definition of done:** engine runs on a small hand-built task set without errors, metrics
dataclass populates correctly, defensive budget-overrun check exists and is tested.

