## Phase 7 — Experiment orchestration (the sweep)

```
Implement amc_tasksim/experiments/sweep.py to run the full experiment:

- U in [0.05, 0.10, ..., 0.95] (configurable)
- N in [10, 100, 1000, 10000, 100000] (configurable, log-spaced)
- 1000 replicate task sets per (U, N) combination, generated once per U (task-set generation
  does not depend on N — only the simulation's execution-time model does) and then simulated
  once per N value, to avoid regenerating task sets redundantly. Structure the code so each
  (taskset_replicate, U) is generated once and reused across all N values in that sweep.
- hi_mode as a top-level CLI/config flag so the whole sweep can be re-run under both
  "fixed_ratio" and "drs_independent" for comparison.
- Parallelise across replicates (not across ticks within a single simulation run) using
  multiprocessing/joblib, since the simulator itself is inherently sequential per task set.
  Use a progress bar (tqdm) at the level of (U, N) combinations.
- Before running the full 1000-replicate sweep, provide a --quick flag that runs e.g. 20
  replicates so the pipeline can be smoke-tested end-to-end quickly.
- Store results as a single tidy pandas DataFrame / parquet file with one row per
  (U, N, hi_mode, replicate_index) containing: all generation parameters, HDM, JNE, LDM, TiD,
  NiD, total HI-releases, total HI-trigger-events, and whether the task set passed the
  is_nontrivial_amc_taskset filter from Phase 4 (store this as a column rather than filtering
  silently, so both filtered and unfiltered analyses are possible later).
- IMPORTANT — statistical power check: after each (U, N) combination completes, compute and log
  the total number of HI-trigger events observed across all 1000 replicates. If this falls below
  some threshold (e.g. 100 events, configurable), print a clear warning that NiD/TiD/JNE
  estimates for this (U, N) cell may be unreliable due to too few rare-event occurrences given
  the simulation duration — do not silently report a smooth-looking but statistically vacuous
  average.

Run the --quick version end-to-end and show me a summary (row count, a few example rows, and
any statistical-power warnings triggered).
```

**Definition of done:** `--quick` sweep completes, produces a results file, and the
statistical-power warning logic demonstrably triggers for at least the largest N value (this is
expected and fine — it tells you where you need either longer duration or more replicates).

