## Phase 9 (optional, extension) — Pluggable scheduler variants: AMC-RH / AMC-RA

```
Extend the ModeChangeProtocol interface from Phase 5 with two additional variants, from
docs/AMCRRTAS2022.pdf Section IV:

- AMC-RH: enter degraded mode when an active HI-criticality job of task tau_i reaches Ri(LO)
  (its LO-criticality response time, computed in Phase 4) since the start of the priority
  level-i busy period in which it was released (not since its own release, and not on raw
  Ci(LO) execution). Exit degraded mode as soon as there is no such active HI-criticality job
  still past its Ri(LO) marker.
- AMC-RA: same entry trigger as AMC-RH, but exit only on an idle instant (as in the original
  AMC scheme).

This requires tracking, per active job, the start time of its priority level-i busy period — see
Appendix B of docs/AMCRRTAS2022.pdf for the O(1)-per-release bookkeeping approach (inherit busy-
period start time from the next-higher-priority active task in the run-queue) and the expiry-
queue mechanism for triggering mode-change transitions.

Re-run the Phase 7 sweep (at least --quick scale) with all three protocols (original AMC,
AMC-RH, AMC-RA) and confirm qualitatively that AMC-RH/AMC-RA reduce NiD, TiD, and JNE+LDM
relative to original AMC, consistent with Table I of docs/AMCRRTAS2022.pdf (AMC-RH reducing
JNE+LDM to roughly 2.5% of the original AMC value for semi-harmonic periods) — exact
reproduction isn't the goal since your task model and duration differ, but the direction and
rough magnitude of the effect should match.
```

**Definition of done:** all three protocols runnable through the same sweep infrastructure;
AMC-RH shows a clear, large reduction in JNE+LDM relative to original AMC in your own data.
